Ugh. A setter on a widget is always a code smell - you have no idea when anyone is going to call it. Can we not use a refresh event instead, and have the widget set this internally? Same comment for PaidInfoTabWidget method below
	/**
	 * This setter is required to set update the {@link LeavePlanPaidLeave} upon task hiding and displaying
	 *
	 * @see PaidLeavePlanRefreshEvent
	 * @see PaidLeavePlanRefreshListener
	 * @see LeavePlanTabStripWidget#refreshEventOccurred(com.fineos.common.portalinfrastructure.event.RefreshEvent)
	 * @param leavePlanPaidLeave
	 */
	public void setLeavePlanPaidLeave(final LeavePlanPaidLeave leavePlanPaidLeave) {
		paidInfoWidget.setLeavePlanPaidLeave(leavePlanPaidLeave);
		waitingPeriodWidget.setLeavePlanPaidLeave(leavePlanPaidLeave);
	}

    And for LeavePlanTabStripWidget.refreshEventOccurred(), which is where all this starts.

Each widget that is interested in the event should register for as a listener, and handle the event themselves, rather than the tab handling it and calling unexpected setters.

